# justfile template

The following is the canonical starting point for a `justfile` in Patterson AI Pets repositories. Copy it to the repository root, adjust task bodies for the specific repository, and keep the verb conventions consistent across the project.

```just
# Patterson AI Pets justfile
# Default task: show available commands
default:
    @just --list

# Install all dependencies and verify the environment
bootstrap:
    mise install
    bun install
    @just verify

# Verify that every required tool is available
verify:
    #!/usr/bin/env bash
    set -euo pipefail
    echo "Checking environment..."
    command -v bun >/dev/null || { echo "bun missing"; exit 1; }
    command -v gh >/dev/null || { echo "gh missing"; exit 1; }
    command -v claude >/dev/null || { echo "claude missing"; exit 1; }
    command -v opencode >/dev/null || { echo "opencode missing"; exit 1; }
    command -v copilot >/dev/null || { echo "copilot missing"; exit 1; }
    echo "Environment OK"

# Run the practice challenge locally
race:
    bun run scripts/race.ts

# Submit this pet to the Show
submit:
    bun run scripts/submit.ts

# Run the pet's test suite
test:
    bun test

# Lint and format
lint:
    bun run lint
    bun run format

# Validate the skill structure against the spec
validate:
    bunx patterson-skill-creator validate .

# Clean local artifacts
clean:
    rm -rf node_modules .bun dist
```

## Guidance for filling out the template

The verb conventions are consistent across Patterson AI Pets repositories. `bootstrap` installs dependencies and verifies the environment. `verify` is a separate task because it is used both during bootstrap and as a standalone sanity check. `race` runs the pet against the practice challenge locally. `submit` opens a pull request to the Show. `test`, `lint`, and `clean` follow their conventional meanings.

Keep task bodies short. If a task grows beyond a few lines, move the body into a script under `scripts/` and invoke the script from the task. This keeps the `justfile` readable and makes the underlying logic testable.

Use `set -euo pipefail` in any inline bash script that has more than a single command. Silent failure is the most common source of confusion in `justfile` debugging, and these three options collectively eliminate the silent failure modes.

The `default` task shows the list of available commands and is the convention across `just`-based projects. Keep this as the first task in the file so contributors who type `just` without arguments see the full list immediately.
